Loneliness, also termed Perceived Social Isolation (PSI), has become of worldwide concern, impacting on health, and affecting all groups from adolescents to especially the elderly. Self-isolation and social distancing are necessary and a recommendation during the Covid-19 pandemic, but may increase the loneliness levels, what may have a negative impact on health (
 Baker and Clark, 2020; 
 Berg-Weger and Morley, 2020; 
 Holt-Lunstand et al., 2015). It has been demonstrated in different animal models. Plasma corticosterone levels correlated significantly with plasma ACTH and with adrenal corticosterone levels in socially isolated (caged) rats (
 Prelló et al., 2006). In a zebrafish model, neurochemical analyses showed that serotonin levels increased when fish were exposed to social stimulus after acute isolation, but its metabolite 5HIAA decreased in response to social stimulus following both acute and chronic isolation. Dopamine levels were also reduced in fish exposed to social stimulus after acute and chronic isolation (
 Shams et al., 2017).
